This book describes how Ancient Greeks tried to interpretate **natural phenomena** under a ‘(proto)-scientific’ perspective. The authors also make a comparison with previous Mesopotamian approaches in understanding natural phenomena.
 
[The comparison between the Greek and Mesopotamian approaches to natural phenomena reveals how in the Ancient Near East such events were basically related to the religious sphere; nevertheless, ancient Mesopotamians, besides a simplistic dichotomy, have already tried to interpretate natural phenomena going beyond their religious background.]

